over the previous 20 years.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this study design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Randomised controlled trial","Cohort study","Cross-sectional study","Ecological study","Case control study"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecase control study\u003C/strong\u003E because it starts with people who have the disease (cases) and compares them to people without the disease (controls), looking backwards in time at potential exposures or risk factors. Case control studies are particularly suitable for investigating rare diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECohort study\u003C/strong\u003E - Cohort studies follow groups forward in time from exposure to outcome. These can be either prospective (following participants into the future) or retrospective (using historical data)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross-sectional study\u003C/strong\u003E - Cross-sectional studies measure exposure and outcome at the same time point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandomised controlled trial\u003C/strong\u003E - RCTs actively assign interventions to participants and follow them forward\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcological study\u003C/strong\u003E - Ecological studies examine populations rather than individuals\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Case control studies compare people with a disease (cases) to those without (controls) to identify potential risk factors.","Case control studies are retrospective, looking back in time to assess exposures that occurred before disease onset.","Case control studies are particularly useful for rare diseases or when there is a long latency between exposure and disease."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60535"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60535"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T20:51:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:36:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75028"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{